  - m_Id: 959272947712
    m_Localized: "<color=#610078><size=60>Working Hours</size></color>\r\n\r\nThe
      maximum working hours allowed is 40 hours per week, which can be distributed
      as the parties wish, provided that daily and weekly rest periods are respected.\r\n\r\nIn
      addition to this ordinary working day, for live-in workers, periods of availability
      can be established at the employer's disposal for a maximum of 20 hours per
      week or for longer periods if compensated with time off.\r\n\r\n<color=#610078><size=60>Hourly
      Work</size></color>\r\n\r\nWork is considered hourly when the total number
      of days providing services to the same employer in a year does not exceed 120.
      It is also mandatory to have a written contract and to provide a salary receipt.\r\n\r\n<color=#610078><size=60>Periods
      of Availability</size></color>\r\n\r\nThe time of presence is that working
      time during which the employee is available to perform a task but is not actively
      working. It must be compensated according to what the parties agree upon.\r\n\r\nIt
      must be paid at least the same amount as an ordinary hour of work or can be
      compensated with paid time off, meaning granting as many hours of free time
      as hours of presence that have been provided.\r\n\r\n<color=#610078><size=60>Extraordinary
      Working Hours: Payment, Limits, and Obligation</size></color>\r\n\r\nExtraordinary
      hours are those that exceed the ordinary working hours established in the contract.
      It is important to remember that the ordinary working day cannot exceed 40
      hours per week, and any hour worked beyond this limit is considered extraordinary.\r\n\r\nExtraordinary
      hours are different from periods of availability; they must be paid separately
      and cannot exceed 80 hours per year.\r\n\r\nAccording to Article 15 of the
      Workers' Statute, extraordinary hours must be paid at least at the same value
      as one ordinary hour of the Minimum Interprofessional Salary.\r\n\r\nIn addition
      to cash payment, the employer can opt to compensate extraordinary hours with
      equivalent rest days, offering free time for the extraordinary hours worked.\r\n\r\nThere
      is a limit of 80 extraordinary hours per year; however, if the option to compensate
      extraordinary hours with free time is chosen, these do not count within the
      mentioned limit. Extraordinary hours are voluntary unless they have been agreed
      upon as mandatory in the employment contract.\r\n\r\n<color=#610078><size=60>Rest
      Periods</size></color>\r\n\r\nThe worker must have the following rest periods:\r\n\r\n\u25CF
      Between two working days on two different days: a minimum of 12 hours, which
      may be reduced to 10 for live-in workers.\r\n\r\n\u25CF Daily rest for live-in
      workers: They will have 2 hours each day for main meals. These rest periods
      do not count as working time.\r\n\r\n\u25CF Weekly rest: 36 consecutive hours.\r\n\r\nSOURCES:\r\n\r\n<color=blue><u><link=https://www.caritasalamanca.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FOLLETO-INFORMATIVO-2024.pdf>https://www.caritasalamanca.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FOLLETO-INFORMATIVO-2024.pdf</link>\r\n\r\n<link=https://www.cuestioneslaborales.es/las-horas-extraordinarias-las-empleadas-del-hogar/>https://www.cuestioneslaborales.es/las-horas-extraordinarias-las-empleadas-del-hogar/</link>\r\n\r\n<link=https://www.cuestioneslaborales.es/horario-de-las-empleadas-del-hogar-internas/>https://www.cuestioneslaborales.es/horario-de-las-empleadas-del-hogar-internas/</link>\r\n\r\n<link=https://www.cuestioneslaborales.es/el-regimen-laboral-de-las-empleadas-del-hogar/#descanso>https://www.cuestioneslaborales.es/el-regimen-laboral-de-las-empleadas-del-hogar/#descanso</link></u></color>\r\n"
