  - m_Id: 1083097190400
    m_Localized: "<color=#610078><align=left><size=60>Holidays and Leave</size></align></color>\r\n\r\n   
      All workers have the right to enjoy at least 30 calendar days of vacation per
      year. This right is maintained regardless of the number of weekly working hours
      or the type of contract (full-time, part-time, or half-time).\r\n\r\n    These
      30 days are accrued throughout the working year, with each month of work generating
      2.5 vacation days.\r\n\r\n    During vacation days, the employee is entitled
      to receive the same salary they would if they were working.\r\n\r\n    There
      is also a right to enjoy 14 public holidays per year, like the rest of the
      workers. The labor calendar varies according to the autonomous community and
      locality.\r\n\r\n<color=#610078><align=left><size=60>How can I enjoy my vacation?</size></align></color>\r\n\r\n   
      Vacations can be divided into fractions as convenient. Legislation establishes
      that at least 15 calendar days must be taken consecutively. However, in practice,
      other arrangements can be agreed upon between both parties.\r\n\r\n    It is
      important to highlight that all vacations must be taken within the same calendar
      year in which they were accrued; they cannot be accumulated from one year to
      another.\r\n\r\n<color=#610078><align=left><size=60>Obligations during Vacation</size></align></color>\r\n\r\n   
      During vacations, the employee has no labor obligations to the employer. It
      is a rest period in which they are not expected to perform any work-related
      tasks.\r\n\r\n    For live-in employees, this means they are not obliged to
      reside at the family home or any other place associated with the job during
      this time.\r\n\r\n    If the employer's family goes on vacation to another
      place and the employee travels with them, does this time count as vacation?
      No, vacation time is rest time for the employee; therefore, if they accompany
      the family during their vacation and continue to perform their work functions
      at the location where the family is traveling, this time does not count as
      vacation but rather as work.\r\n\r\n    Should the live-in employee accompany
      the employer's family to the home during the family's vacation? The rules regarding
      overnight stays for live-in employees are part of the essential elements of
      the contract, so if during a period of the year these overnight stays must
      occur in a place different from the usual residence, this matter should be
      specified in the contract.\r\n\r\n    In any case, this time will not count
      as vacation for the employee as long as they continue to carry out their work
      tasks.\r\n\r\n<color=#610078><align=left><size=60>Paid Leave for Domestic Workers</size></align></color>\r\n\r\n   
      People working in domestic employment have the right to certain paid leave
      that allows them to perform their work without jeopardizing their labor and
      economic stability. These leaves are provided for in the Workers' Statute and
      cover a series of situations:\r\n\r\n\u25CF Marriage: 15 calendar days\r\n\r\n\u25CF
      Family reasons: 2 days (if the worker needs to travel, the leave is extended
      to 4 calendar days)\r\n\r\n\u25CB Death \r\n\r\n\u25CB Serious accident or
      illness\r\n\r\n\u25CB Hospitalization\r\n\r\n\u25CB Surgical intervention without
      hospitalization that requires home rest for relatives up to the second degree
      of consanguinity or affinity\r\n\r\n\u25CF Moving house: 1 day of leave\r\n\r\n\u25CF
      Right to be absent due to an unavoidable duty: the right to be absent from
      work for the necessary time to fulfill an unavoidable public and personal duty,
      including active suffrage, is recognized.\r\n\r\n\u25CF Leave related to pregnancy
      and infant care: during pregnancy, domestic workers have the right to the necessary
      leave to attend prenatal examinations and childbirth preparation techniques.\r\n\r\n\u25CF
      Birth, adoption, custody for adoption purposes, or fostering: 1 hour of absence
      from work is granted, which can be divided into two parts, for the care of
      the infant until they reach 9 months. The duration of the leave will increase
      proportionally in the case of multiple births, adoptions, custody for adoption
      purposes, or fostering.\r\n\r\nSOURCES:\r\n\r\n<color=blue><align=left><u><link=https://www.caritasalamanca.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FOLLETO-INFORMATIVO-2024.pdf>https://www.caritasalamanca.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/FOLLETO-INFORMATIVO-2024.pdf</link>\r\n\r\n<link=https://www.mites.gob.es/es/portada/serviciohogar/preguntas-frecuentes/tiempo-trabajo/index.htm>https://www.mites.gob.es/es/portada/serviciohogar/preguntas-frecuentes/tiempo-trabajo/index.htm</link>\r\n\r\n<link=https://www.cuestioneslaborales.es/las-vacaciones-las-empleadas-del-hogar/#horas>https://www.cuestioneslaborales.es/las-vacaciones-las-empleadas-del-hogar/#horas</link>\r\n\r\n<link=https://www.boe.es/buscar/pdf/2015/BOE-A-2015-11430-consolidado.pdf>https://www.boe.es/buscar/pdf/2015/BOE-A-2015-11430-consolidado.pdf</link></u></align></color>\r\n"
