    m_Localized: "<color=#610078><align=left><size=60>Work Leaves</size></align></color>\r\n\r\n<color=#610078><align=left><size=60>A.
      New Medical Leave Regulations</size></align></color>\r\n\r\n    The new Royal
      Decree 1060/2022 introduces major changes that directly affect the management
      of temporary disability situations (medical leave), including in the domestic
      workers sector. The significant changes introduced by this new regulation are:\r\n\r\n\u25CF
      The obligation for the worker to submit the medical leave report to their employer
      is eliminated. The medical leave report for companies/employers is removed.
      Instead, the doctor will be responsible for providing the medical leave report
      to the worker and communicating the leave data to the INSS or mutuals, which
      in turn will transmit the information to employers electronically.\r\n\r\n\u25CF
      Doctors may establish shorter medical review periods than those officially
      set, as long as they align with the progress of the condition.\r\n\r\n\u25CF
      The data that companies must transmit to Social Security are modified.\r\n\r\n   
      Among these changes, the one that most directly affects the domestic workers
      sector is related to medical reports. Until now, when a worker went to their
      general practitioner or mutual to collect their sick leave, confirmation, or
      discharge reports, the doctor always provided the worker with two copies: one
      copy for the worker and another copy for the company. The worker then had 3
      days to provide this report to the company, so that the company would be aware
      of the situation and could take the necessary steps.\r\n\r\n    With the entry
      into force of this new Royal Decree on April 1, 2023, the only report issued
      by the general practitioner will be the worker's copy. This report is confidential
      for the worker and does not need to be provided to the company.\r\n\r\n   
      Therefore, as of April 1, the general practitioner communicates the medical
      leave data to the INSS electronically within 24 working hours of the appointment
      with the worker. Once the data is received, the INSS transmits this information
      to the employers.\r\n\r\n<color=#610078><align=left><size=60>B. Temporary Disability
      and Medical Leave</size></align></color>\r\n\r\n    When a worker enters a
      temporary disability situation, the employer must initiate several important
      steps. First, they must stay informed about the worker\u2019s leave situation
      (leave dates and confirmations), as these will be necessary for adjusting the
      medical leave.\r\n\r\n    During the medical leave period, the worker is not
      obliged to provide services and is entitled to receive financial compensation
      for temporary disability, the amount of which will depend on the regulatory
      base and the duration of the leave.\r\n\r\n    The employer must be informed
      about the entity responsible for covering common and professional contingencies.
      This entity can be the INSS or a Mutual Collaborator of Social Security. When
      registering as a domestic employer, one of these options must be chosen.\r\n\r\n<color=#610078><align=left><size=60>C.
      Coverage of Common Contingencies</size></align></color>\r\n\r\n    In the case
      of common contingencies, which include temporary disability coverage for common
      illness or non-occupational accident, the general practitioner will be the
      one to issue the medical leave report to the worker, carry out the reviews,
      and determine when they can issue the medical discharge.\r\n\r\n    Regarding
      the caregiver's payroll management, it should be noted that:\r\n\r\n\u25CF
      The worker does not receive a salary for the first 3 days of leave.\r\n\r\n\u25CF
      From the 4th to the 8th day, they will receive 60% of the contribution base
      from the employer.\r\n\r\n\u25CF From the 9th day onward, the worker will receive
      a benefit directly from the entity covering common contingencies. In this case,
      the worker must go to the nearest INSS/Mutual to manage the payment of their
      benefit, providing the employer with an employer certificate to process the
      payment.\r\n\r\n    It is important to highlight that, to be eligible for the
      benefit, the worker must have contributed for 180 days in the last 6 years.
      If this requirement is not met, the worker will not receive any benefits during
      their medical leave.\r\n"
