  - m_Id: 1396826935296
    m_Localized: "<color=#610078><align=left><size=60>D. Coverage of Professional
      Contingencies</size></align></color>\r\n\r\n    Professional contingencies
      refer to protection in cases of work-related accidents, defined as \"any bodily
      injury that the worker suffers on the occasion of or as a consequence of the
      work performed for others\" (art. 115 LGSS). If a worker suffers a work-related
      accident, they must go directly to the entity responsible for the corresponding
      coverage.\r\n\r\n    If the coverage of professional contingencies is handled
      by the INSS, the worker must go to the general practitioner to obtain the medical
      leave report, and the same doctor will be responsible for the reviews and the
      discharge report. If the coverage is provided by a mutual insurance company,
      the mutual's doctor will issue the medical leave report and carry out the relevant
      reviews.\r\n\r\n    Regarding compensation for work-related accidents, the
      employer will cover the first day of leave at 100%, while from the second day
      onward, the INSS or the mutual will be responsible for direct payment. The
      employer must prepare the employer's certificate and provide it to the worker
      so they can manage the payment of their compensation.\r\n\r\n    In the case
      of work-related accidents, the employer is obligated to report the accident
      through the Delt@ System within 5 working days from the date of the accident
      or from when they become aware of it.\r\n"
