    m_Localized: "<color=#610078></align=left><size=60>Termination of Employment</color></size></align>\r\n\r\n<color=#610078></align=left><size=60>a.
      Termination in Home Employment</color></size></align>\r\n\r\nOne of the main
      demands in the domestic employment sector was the abolition of the legal concept
      of termination without cause, which allowed employers to terminate the employment
      contract without needing to justify the reason. This concept was almost exclusive
      to the household sector, since, as a rule in labor law, dismissals must be
      justified by one of the reasons outlined in the Workers' Statute.\r\n\r\n<color=#610078></align=left><size=60>b.
      Reasons for Termination in Home Employment</color></size></align>\r\n\r\nAs
      of September 9, 2022, the concept of termination without cause was abolished,
      removing the possibility for employers to terminate contracts without justification.
      The new reasons for termination in domestic employment must always be motivated
      and justified.\r\n\r\nThese reasons include:\r\n\r\n- **Objective termination
      due to a decrease in income or increase in expenses in the family unit:** 
      \r\n  The contract can be terminated when, due to unforeseen circumstances,
      the family's income decreases or their expenses increase, such as when a family
      member loses a job or an unexpected expense occurs.\r\n\r\n- **Objective termination
      due to changes in family needs:**  \r\n  The contract can be terminated when
      the family makes a decision that affects its structure, like deciding to place
      an elderly family member in a specialized care center.\r\n\r\n- **Objective
      termination due to loss of trust in the employee's conduct:**  \r\n  There
      must be a serious cause attributed to the employee that leads to a genuine
      loss of trust, justifying the decision to end the employment.\r\n\r\n<color=#610078></align=left><size=60>c.
      Voluntary Resignation:</color></size></align>\r\n\r\nVoluntary resignation
      occurs when a household employee notifies the employer, either in writing or
      verbally, of their decision to end the employment relationship. In this case,
      the decision comes from the employee, and the employer only needs to be informed.
      The resignation process requires fulfilling certain requirements and considering
      specific factors.\r\n\r\nKey features include:\r\n\r\n- The notice must be
      given 15 calendar days in advance.\r\n- The company must still pay a final
      settlement even in cases of voluntary resignation.\r\n- The resignation is
      reversible within 15 days.\r\n- A new contract must be signed if the employee
      wishes to return to the same employer.\r\n\r\nEmployees must sign the voluntary
      resignation form willingly, without pressure or external causes, as any form
      of coercion is illegal. Additionally, voluntary resignations disqualify the
      employee from claiming unemployment benefits, except when they find a new job
      but fail to pass the probationary period, and more than three months have passed
      since the resignation.\r\n\r\nUpon the resignation, the employer must notify
      the TGSS through the Import@ss portal, which will issue a certificate of employment
      to be submitted to SEPE within 15 days. This certificate is essential for unemployment
      benefits unless the resignation is voluntary.\r\n\r\n<color=#610078></align=left><size=60>d.
      Dismissal Procedure:</color></size></align>\r\n\r\nIt is crucial to follow
      the correct dismissal procedure to avoid the dismissal being deemed improper.
      The steps include:\r\n\r\n- **Providing written notice:**  \r\n  A written
      notice of 7 days must be given, or 20 days if the employee has been working
      for more than a year. If not provided, these days must be compensated in the
      final settlement.\r\n  \r\n- **Dismissal letter:**  \r\n  A dismissal letter
      must clearly state the reason for termination and include justification for
      the decision. It should not only state the intention to terminate but also
      provide a rationale.\r\n\r\n- **Compensation and final settlement:**  \r\n 
      Compensation of 12 days of salary per year of service, up to six months, must
      be paid, along with the salary for the days worked, unpaid vacation, and other
      entitlements.\r\n\r\n- **Signing documentation:**  \r\n  All documentation
      must be signed by both parties. If the employee refuses to sign, a witness
      should be present to confirm the date of communication, and the documents can
      be sent via certified mail.\r\n\r\nIt is essential to follow these procedures
      to avoid an improper dismissal, which could entitle the employee to a compensation
      of 20 days' salary per year of service, up to a limit of 12 months.\r\n\r\nSOURCES: 
      \r\n\r\n<color=blue></align=left><u><link=https://www.cuidum.com/blog/nueva-normativa-en-la-extincion-contrato-empleada-del-hogar/>https://www.cuidum.com/blog/nueva-normativa-en-la-extincion-contrato-empleada-del-hogar/</link></u></color></align=left>\r\n\r\n<color=blue></align=left><u><link=https://www.sepe.es/HomeSepe/empresas/servicios-para-empresas/certificados.html>https://www.sepe.es/HomeSepe/empresas/servicios-para-empresas/certificados.html</link></u></color></align=left>\r\n\r\n<color=blue></align=left><u><link=https://aiudo.es/baja-voluntaria-en-las-empleadas-del-hogar/>https://aiudo.es/baja-voluntaria-en-las-empleadas-del-hogar/</link></u></color></align=left>\r\n"
